# Python Production Rules

You are writing production Python. Optimize for readability, correctness, and explicit contracts.

## Typing Requirements
- Add type hints to all function and method parameters and return values.
- Avoid untyped public APIs; use `typing`/`collections.abc` for clear interfaces.
- Prefer `TypedDict`, `Protocol`, and `Literal` where they improve domain clarity.
- Do not use `Any` unless unavoidable; document why when used.

## Docstrings (Google Style)
- Every public module, class, and function must include a Google-style docstring.
- Include `Args`, `Returns`, and `Raises` sections when applicable.
- Keep docstrings concise and behavior-focused; avoid repeating obvious type info.

## Paths and Filesystem
- Use `pathlib.Path` instead of `os.path`.
- Accept and return `Path` objects for internal file APIs where practical.
- Use context managers for file operations.

## Data Modeling
- Prefer `@dataclass` for structured internal data objects.
- Use Pydantic models for validated external input/output boundaries.
- Keep model validation close to I/O boundaries (API, CLI, file parse).
- Avoid passing raw dict payloads deep into domain logic.

## Error Handling
- Raise specific exception types; avoid bare `except` and generic `Exception` catches.
- Catch errors at boundaries and convert them into actionable, domain-specific failures.
- Add context when re-raising (`raise ... from err`) to preserve traceback chains.
- Do not use exceptions for normal control flow.

## Async and Concurrency
- Use `asyncio` for I/O-bound concurrency, not CPU-bound parallelism.
- Prefer `async`/`await` end-to-end instead of mixing sync wrappers without need.
- Use `asyncio.gather`/`TaskGroup` with explicit cancellation and timeout handling.
- Avoid blocking calls in async code; use async-compatible clients/libraries.

## Imports and Module Hygiene
- Import order: 1) standard library, 2) third-party packages, 3) local application imports.
- Separate each import group with one blank line.
- Keep top-level imports side-effect free.
- Avoid wildcard imports.

## Formatting and File Size
- Enforce max line length: 88 characters (Black-compatible).
- Use Black formatting and Ruff/Flake8 lint rules consistent with project config.
- Target max file length: 350 lines; refactor modules that exceed this without clear reason.
- Keep functions small and single-purpose.

## Testing (Pytest)
- Use `pytest` for unit and integration tests.
- Name tests by behavior (`test_returns_cached_value_when_fresh`).
- Use fixtures for setup reuse; keep fixtures scoped as narrowly as possible.
- Cover success paths, failure paths, and boundary conditions.
- Mock only external systems (network, DB, filesystem time), not core logic.

## Delivery Expectations
- Code must pass formatter, linter, type checker, and pytest.
- Favor explicitness and maintainability over terse clever code.
